       Drawings output formats

       By default, when a drawing is requested, it is outputted in pdf format.
       Since graphviz allows other output formats (see http://www.graphviz.org/doc/info/output.html), it is possible to also request a drawing in a format other than pdf.




	This is a global variable which holds the valid output formats for a drawing. It currently has the value: ["dia", "fig", "gd", "gd2", "gif", "hpgl", "jpg", "mif", "mp", "pcl", "pic", "plain", "plain-ext", "png", "ps", "ps2", "svg", "svgz", "vrml", "vtx", "wbmp", "none"] (see http://www.graphviz.org/doc/info/output.html for their description).







	This is a global variable which holds the alternative output format for a drawing.
	By default its value is "none" which indicates that just pdf will be used
	as the output format.


	If its value becomes one of those in , then
	besides the pdf file, it will also be created a file in the alternative format.


	To change this variable's value, please use .







	This function is used to set the value of  to the
format f which is one of .

gap> DrawingsExtraFormat;
"none"
gap> SetDrawingsExtraFormat("jpg");
gap> DrawingsExtraFormat;
"jpg"

gap> DrawRightCayleyGraph(poi3);
Displaying file: /tmp/tmp.tpJqvI/cayleygraph.dot.ps
The extra output format file: /tmp/tmp.tpJqvI/cayleygraph.dot.jpg
has also been created.










            Drawings extra graph attributes
	    The functions described in this subsection are intended to give the user a finer control
	    over the final drawing.
	    They allow to define the graph attributes described in http://graphviz.org/doc/info/attrs.html.
	    (Note that only graph attributes are allowed to be defined, not edge nor node attributes are supported yet.)




	  This is a global variable which holds a list of strings, each of which defines a dot graph attribute.
	  This variable is not intended to be modified by the user directly, but can be used to check
	  which extra attributes are currently defined.
	  To set the attributes, please use .
	  If DrawingsExtraGraphAttributes holds the value "none" then the default dot settings will be used.
	  Use  to set it to "none".







	  This is the function to define the drawing's graph attributes (see http://graphviz.org/doc/info/attrs.html
	  for a list and explanation of them).
	  the argument L is a list of strings, each of which defines a dot graph attribute.
	  For example, if we wanted to define the graph size to be 7x9 (in inches), we would call
	  SetDrawingsExtraGraphAttributes(["size=7,9"]);.


	  If we also wanted to define the graph to be displayed in landscape mode we would call
	  SetDrawingsExtraGraphAttributes(["size=7,9", "rotate=90"]);.
	  If, in addition we wanted to define the background colour to be, for example, pink, we would call
	  SetDrawingsExtraGraphAttributes(["size=7,9", "rotate=90", "bgcolor=pink"]);.


	  After defining the attributes, any command that creates a drawing will use the last defined attributes.
	  To set them back to the defaults, please use .

gap> DrawingsExtraGraphAttributes;
"none"


gap> SetDrawingsExtraGraphAttributes(["size=7,9"]);

gap> DrawingsExtraGraphAttributes;
[ "size=7,9" ]


gap> SetDrawingsExtraGraphAttributes(["size=7,9", "rotate=90"]);

gap> DrawingsExtraGraphAttributes;
[ "size=7,9", "rotate=90" ]


gap> SetDrawingsExtraGraphAttributes(["size=7,9", "rotate=90", "bgcolor=pink"]);

gap> DrawingsExtraGraphAttributes;
[ "size=7,9", "rotate=90", "bgcolor=pink" ]


gap> ClearDrawingsExtraGraphAttributes();

gap> DrawingsExtraGraphAttributes;
"none"







	  This function sets the graph drawing attributes back to dot's defaults.
